54
00:02:22.980 --> 00:02:28.980
Now, if you've spent time with a baby, you've probably noticed how much they move their little arms and legs.

55
00:02:28.980 --> 00:02:35.980
Here, Marida Rome explains the meaning of these movements to BBC Radio full program, woman's hour.

56
00:02:35.980 --> 00:02:41.980
75% of their movement are intentional synchronized.

57
00:02:41.980 --> 00:02:43.980
They're not jerky.

58
00:02:43.980 --> 00:02:47.980
We know to the naked eye, they're pulled the appear very jerky.

59
00:02:47.980 --> 00:02:48.980
But they're not.

60
00:02:48.980 --> 00:02:53.980
They're there to bring us in the parents, they need us.

61
00:02:53.980 --> 00:02:59.980
So they, all those movements are there to say, look, come, look at me.

62
00:02:59.980 --> 00:03:00.980
I need you.

63
00:03:00.980 --> 00:03:02.980
I want you to, you know, to play with you.

64
00:03:02.980 --> 00:03:06.980
Babies move their arms and legs to create a bond with their parents.

65
00:03:06.980 --> 00:03:09.980
To the naked eye, these movements look jerky.

66
00:03:09.980 --> 00:03:13.980
An adjective meaning sudden and quick, not smooth flowing.

67
00:03:13.980 --> 00:03:19.980
The phrase to the naked eye means, in a way, that can be seen without special instruments like a microscope,

68
00:03:19.980 --> 00:03:22.980
or is seen in the way an ordinary person would.

69
00:03:22.980 --> 00:03:29.980
In reality, these jerky movements are intentional, meaning that their planned and done for a particular purpose.

70
00:03:29.980 --> 00:03:33.980
To catch their parents' attention, say they will be noticed and cared for.

71
00:03:33.980 --> 00:03:38.980
Marie's book is aimed at new parents who are learning to understand their baby's body language.

72
00:03:38.980 --> 00:03:43.980
But she also has advice for parents who are finding it difficult to bond with their newborn.

73
00:03:43.980 --> 00:03:47.980
And she explains here to BBC Radio 4 program, Woman's Hour.

74
00:03:47.980 --> 00:03:50.980
Parenting is really hard, falling in love with this little baby.

75
00:03:50.980 --> 00:03:58.980
It's not, you know, this idea that love at first sight, I think it's such an helpful cliché.

76
00:03:58.980 --> 00:04:03.980
It will take time to love that baby, to get to know that baby.

77
00:04:03.980 --> 00:04:08.980
Many new parents dream about falling in love with their baby at first sight.

78
00:04:08.980 --> 00:04:14.980
The idiom love at first sight means being in love with someone as soon as you see them for the first time.

79
00:04:14.980 --> 00:04:18.980
But Marie thinks this ideal dream can cause problems.

80
00:04:18.980 --> 00:04:20.980
She calls it an unhelpful cliché.

81
00:04:20.980 --> 00:04:28.980
A cliché is an overused phrase or comment that has been said so much that it's become unoriginal and uninteresting.

82
00:04:28.980 --> 00:04:30.980
And in some cases, unhelpful.

83
00:04:30.980 --> 00:04:37.980
For example, by creating unrealistic expectations or by making parents feel guilty, they're not doing enough.

84
00:04:37.980 --> 00:04:42.980
Marie says it takes time to get to know a newborn baby and to fall in love.

85
00:04:42.980 --> 00:04:50.980
But for most parents, all the misunderstandings, sleepless nights and dirty nappies are worth it for their amazing baby.

86
00:04:50.980 --> 00:04:55.980
And speaking of amazing babies, what was the correct answer to your question, Beth?

87
00:04:55.980 --> 00:04:59.980
Well, the correct statement was that babies' eyes changed colour.

88
00:04:59.980 --> 00:05:01.980
